        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1977-03-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1977-03-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="149"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d149">
                <head>149. Memorandum From Secretary of Defense <persName corresp="#p_BH_2"
                        >Brown</persName> to the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_BZ_1">Brzezinski</persName>)<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d149fn1">Source: Carter Library, National Security Affairs,
                            <persName corresp="#p_BZ_1">Brzezinski</persName> Material, Subject
                        File, Box 6, Comprehensive Test Ban (<gloss target="#t_CTB_1">CTB</gloss>),
                        3–12/77. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1977-03-05">March 5, 1977</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Conversation with The President on <gloss target="#t_CTB_1">CTB</gloss>
                        Considerations</item>
                </list>
                <p>At your suggestion, I conveyed my misgivings about the peaceful nuclear
                    explosions loophole in <gloss target="#t_CTB_1">CTB</gloss> to the President in
                    a conversation yesterday.<note n="2" xml:id="d149fn2">No record of this
                        conversation has been found. According to the President’s Daily Diary,
                            <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_BH_2">Brown</persName> met from 4:45 to 5:20 p.m. on May 4.
                        (Carter Library, Presidential Materials)</note> Moreover, I described the
                        <gloss target="#t_JCS_1">JCS</gloss> position that a ban on nuclear testing
                    would be contrary to our national security interests. I assured him that I would
                    be working on the broadest, most balanced view possible here in the Defense
                    Department.</p>
                <p>The President agreed that <gloss target="#t_CTB_1">CTB</gloss> would be a useful
                    topic for a luncheon discussion by him with the Joint Chiefs, <persName
                        corresp="#p_DCW_1">Charles Duncan</persName>, you and me.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BH_2">
                            <hi rend="strong">Harold Brown</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="3" xml:id="d149fn3">
                            <persName corresp="#p_BH_2">Brown</persName> signed “<persName
                                corresp="#p_BH_2">Harold</persName>” at the end of the
                            memorandum.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
